     2	
     3	
     4	
     5	---
     6	
     7	You are designing and building a **GPS-denied maritime positioning system** that navigates
     8	from **LEO satellite signals of opportunity** (Starlink, OneWeb, Iridium, Orbcomm), using
     9	**Nuand bladeRF 2.0 micro** SDRs. Work to production engineering standards: this steers a
    10	boat.
    11	
    12	## Mission
    13	
    14	Measure position, velocity and heading on a moving vessel **without GNSS**, from Doppler
    15	(range-rate) observations of LEO downlinks, and fuse them with inertial, speed-log and
    16	heading sensors into a navigation solution good enough to feed an autopilot.
    17	
    18	The honest framing: this is simultaneously a **research instrument** (can LEO SoOP navigate
    19	a boat without GNSS, and how well?) and an **operational navigator**. Those two goals fight
    20	each other. Resolve that tension explicitly and early — see "Failure modes" below.
    21	
    22	## Fixed constraints
    23	
    24	- **SDR: Nuand bladeRF 2.0 micro (xA4 or xA9).** Verify current specs, price and EU
    25	  availability yourself — do not trust my numbers. The properties that matter here:
    26	  - **2×2 coherent MIMO.** Two RX channels on a shared clock. This is the reason to pick
    27	    this radio: RX0 can take the Ku IF (Starlink/OneWeb behind an LNB) while RX1 takes
    28	    L-band (Iridium 1616–1626.5 MHz) **coherently**, eliminating the multi-dongle,
    29	    multi-clock mess that plagues cheaper builds. Exploit this deliberately.
    30	  - **Native 10 MHz external reference input.** Critical — see the clock constraint below.
    31	  - 47 MHz–6 GHz tuning, 12-bit ADC, up to ~61.44 MSPS, USB 3.0, Cyclone V FPGA.
    32	  - Ku band (10.7–12.75 GHz) still requires an LNB to downconvert to the ~950–2150 MHz
    33	    L-band IF. That IF is comfortably inside bladeRF range.
    34	- **Frequency reference: free-running, no GNSS discipline.** A GPSDO defeats the entire
    35	  premise. Use a surplus rubidium (FE-5680A class) or a good OCXO, calibrated
    36	  pre-deployment only. The position solver must carry receiver clock bias and drift as
    37	  estimated states.
    38	- **The vessel is manned.** A qualified person is aboard with a physical manual override.
    39	  This is not a detail — it dissolves the COLREGs Rule 5 lookout obligation that makes an
    40	  unmanned build legally intractable, and it is what makes sea trials possible at all.
    41	- **Autopilot: ArduPilot Rover, boat frame** (`FRAME_CLASS=2`). PX4 has no boat frame and
    42	  its EKF2 external-vision path demands 30–50 Hz or it will not fuse.
    43	
    44	## What is already known — do not rediscover these
    45	
    46	These were established by prior work at real cost. Verify anything you intend to rely on,
    47	but start from here rather than from zero.
    48	
    49	**Signal layer**
    50	- The Starlink Ku **tone comb degraded fleet-wide after 2023** (~50 → ~20 dB-Hz). Do not
    51	  architect around tones. The tractable observable is **beacon / PSS-SSS correlation
    52	  Doppler** at 2.5–5 MHz bandwidth. The sync sequences are published.
    53	- Use **CelesTrak supplemental ephemerides (SupGP)**, not plain TLEs. Confirmed full-fleet
    54	  for Starlink and OneWeb. SGP4 error grows roughly 0.94 km at 6 h, ~2.6 km at 1 day,
    55	  38.5 km at 7 days — cache before going offline and gate on age.
    56	- **Orbcomm (137 MHz) is the best value per dollar** in the constellation set: continuous,
    57	  cheap to receive, deep published SoOP pedigree, and it decorrelates a front end that is
    58	  otherwise entirely dependent on one LNB.
    59	- **OneWeb earns its place on geometry, not on signal count — but it is conditional.**
    60	  At high latitude Starlink's 53° shells produce mostly east–west passes, so the east error
    61	  axis stays poorly observed however many Starlink satellites you track. OneWeb's near-polar
    62	  87.9° orbits run within ~4° of due north–south, near-orthogonal to Starlink: published
    63	  OneWeb-only east sigma of 636.7 m collapses to 3.5 m fused, and single-constellation 2-D
    64	  errors of 30–35 m each fuse to ~5 m with eight satellites (a truth-aided ceiling, but the
    65	  direction is real). Marginal hardware cost is ~zero — same Ku band, same LNB, same IF;
    66	  active channels 11.075/11.325 GHz land at 1325/1575 MHz, and unlike a 1700 MHz-limited
    67	  receiver the bladeRF also reaches 11.575 GHz (IF 1825 MHz).
    68	  **The catch:** there is no demand-proof narrowband OneWeb observable. The trackable 10 ms
    69	  beacon is the demand-dependent default-payload repetition, and beam activity at a fixed
    70	  site pulses in roughly 20-second windows on alternating channels. Energy detection is
    71	  near-certain; continuous trackability is not. **Gate all OneWeb tracker work behind a
    72	  24-hour channel-occupancy survey at the actual operating location** — measure real
    73	  correlation gain before writing a tracker.
    74	- **Spend the second coherent RX channel deliberately, and let that survey decide it.**
    75	  Ku + L-band (Starlink/OneWeb on RX0, Iridium on RX1) maximises constellation diversity and
    76	  decorrelates the front end, since Iridium bypasses the LNB entirely — no shared bias tee,
    77	  no common rain-fade mode. Dual-Ku (two OneWeb channels at once) instead defeats the
    78	  alternating-channel pulsing and roughly doubles OneWeb's usable duty cycle. If OneWeb
    79	  proves reliably present on one channel, take the first option; if it pulses across
    80	  channels as the evidence suggests, take the second and time-share Iridium.
    81	
    82	**Estimation layer — the single most important fact**
    83	- **On a moving receiver, LEO Doppler is a velocity instrument first and a position
    84	  instrument only by accumulation.** Receiver velocity enters range-rate at unit magnitude
    85	  every sample; position enters only through line-of-sight *direction*, suppressed by
    86	  1/range (550–1200 km), and is recoverable only from how the Doppler curve evolves over
    87	  **10–20 minutes**. Every manoeuvre resets convergence. Design the test campaign around
    88	  long constant-heading legs or you will never observe position at all.
    89	- Expect **0.7–4 cm/s per-axis velocity** accuracy and, satellite-only, **~100–200 m
    90	  position** — not the metre-level figures in the literature, which were all obtained with
    91	  **GPS-disciplined** lab receivers.
    92	- **Marine dead-reckoning error is dominated by current set and drift** (0.2–1.0 kn
    93	  typical, 2–4 kn in Danish straits), which is 1.5–6× the heading term. A speed log
    94	  measures speed *through water*; Doppler measures speed *over ground*; differencing them
    95	  yields the current vector directly. This is the strongest argument for LEO Doppler on a
    96	  boat, and it is a **velocity** argument.
    97	- **Heading is the weakest link**, and GNSS compasses are excluded by the premise. Budget
    98	  for it properly: calibrated dual magnetometers including a propulsion-current deviation
    99	  term, and consider a solar/sky-polarisation compass (absolute, non-magnetic, passive).
   100	- **Do not buy a tactical IMU expecting it to carry a passage.** Even navigation-grade
   101	  drifts ~1 km/hour free-inertial. A boat *measures* heading rather than integrating it,
   102	  which breaks the classic inertial divergence mode. The IMU keeps the dynamics model
   103	  honest through turns; it does not carry position.
   104	
   105	**Autopilot integration**
   106	- Inject the solution as **`GPS_INPUT` (MAVLink msg 232, `GPS1_TYPE=14`) at ~5 Hz**, not
   107	  `ODOMETRY`. Reason, verified in ArduPilot source: `handle_odometry()` hard-codes the
   108	  velocity error argument to literal `0` and the decoded velocity covariance is floored to
   109	  a constant, so ODOMETRY **cannot** transport per-epoch velocity uncertainty. Since your
   110	  solution is good in velocity and poor in position, that distinction is decisive.
   111	  `GPS_INPUT` carries `horiz_accuracy` and `speed_accuracy` independently.
   112	- **ArduPilot clamps reported horizontal accuracy at 100 m internally.** Its EKF variance
   113	  is therefore a censored view. The real uncertainty monitor and the steering gate must
   114	  live in your companion process, upstream of MAVLink. This is not tunable away.
   115	- Publish continuously with dead-reckoned fill between absolute fixes; `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` is
   116	  4000 ms, so fixes arriving minutes apart cannot be published raw.
   117	
   118	**Hardware**
   119	- The frequency reference's enemy at sea is **sustained mean tilt, not wave motion**.
   120	  Oscillatory FM is suppressed as 1/(π·f·τ); a sustained heel is a *step* the linear drift
   121	  model cannot absorb. Free ~11× mitigation: mount the resultant g-sensitivity vector
   122	  vertical. If the hull planes and slams, re-derive this — the analysis above assumed a
   123	  displacement hull.
