   138	## Verification discipline
   139	
   140	- Write tests first; loop on `cargo test`/`pytest` and the linter until both pass cleanly.
   141	- **Verify Jacobians numerically against finite differences.** A wrong Jacobian is silent —
   142	  the filter still runs and still produces a covariance, just the wrong one, and that
   143	  covariance gates steering authority.
   144	- Prove the estimator on **replayed real captures** before trusting it, and run the same
   145	  raw log twice — once GNSS-aided, once GNSS-withheld. That delta is the headline result.
   146	- Use **ArduPilot SITL** to validate the MAVLink path against pinned firmware, recording
   147	  the commit hash and artifact checksum.
   148	- Cite sources for factual claims. Mark estimates as estimates. Separate what you measured
   149	  from what you inferred.
   150	
   151	## Failure modes to actively avoid
   152	
   153	These are the specific ways the prior attempt went wrong. Guard against each explicitly.
   154	
   155	1. **GNSS quietly absorbing the project.** If a GNSS receiver is present as a production
   156	   source, the GNSS-denied path becomes a fallback nobody validates, and the research
   157	   question is never answered. Fix: a single `gnss_authority` config key with
   158	   `production | recorded_only | off`, enforced in the fusion path, where `recorded_only`
   159	   routes GNSS to the truth journal and nothing else. Same code in every mode — a research
   160	   mode running different code does not validate the operational mode. An unrecognised
   161	   value must raise, never default to `production`.
   162	2. **Acceptance limits that make the research result fail by construction.** A single 25 m
   163	   position limit is correct operationally and impossible for satellite-only navigation.
   164	   Split acceptance into **aided** and **denied** profiles with limits drawn from the
   165	   literature for each.
   166	3. **A dead-reckoning timeout that forbids convergence.** A 30-second DR gate is right for
   167	   *authority* and fatal for an estimator that needs 10–20 minutes to observe position.
   168	   Let the gate govern authority only, never estimator execution.
   169	4. **Unit-tested modules that are never connected.** The prior build had a filter, a bus, an
   170	   integrity monitor and a supervisor, each with passing tests, and **nothing wired them
   171	   together** — no fusion executive existed. Build the executive first and grow modules into
   172	   it, not the other way round.
   173	5. **Forgetting to propagate.** Related and worse: ensure the filter is actually
   174	   time-propagated from IMU input in the running loop, not only updated when measurements
   175	   arrive. Otherwise the covariance never grows with motion and every uncertainty gate
   176	   reads optimistically.
   177	6. **Building the reject gate before the producer.** A gate that scores observations against
   178	   a prediction nobody produces is decoration. Build the ephemeris propagator and Doppler
   179	   predictor before the gate that consumes them.
   180	7. **Circular validation.** If the LEO residual is scored against a state estimate driven by
   181	   GNSS, accepted residuals measure agreement-with-GNSS, and exactly the measurements that
   182	   would reveal a LEO bias get rejected as outliers. Compute LEO performance statistics only
   183	   from GNSS-withheld runs, offline.
   184	8. **Declaring states you never observe.** Do not carry filter states with no measurement
   185	   path — they accrue process noise unbounded and inflate the state vector without
   186	   informing it. Either implement the update or delete the state.
   187	9. **A safety inversion without a backstop.** On a manned fast boat it is correct that
   188	   software never auto-selects RTL/Loiter/disarm — an unannounced manoeuvre at speed is
   189	   itself the hazard. But "never manoeuvre" must not become "no backstop": give the
   190	   supervisor its own monotonic watchdog so authority cannot outlive the solution, make
   191	   un-acknowledged alarms escalate, and ensure a physical, controller-independent override
   192	   exists (a helm kill-cord is cheap and standard).
   193	10. **Documentation drift.** When the design changes, mark the superseded documents as
   194	    superseded *in the documents themselves*. A demotion recorded only in the new file's
   195	    preamble is invisible to anyone reading top-down — including your future self.
   196	
   197	## Open questions to resolve with live research
   198	
   199	- bladeRF 2.0 micro: current price, EU availability, xA4 vs xA9 FPGA sizing for on-board
   200	  channelisation, sustained USB 3.0 throughput on your chosen host, and the maturity of
   201	  Rust bindings versus going through SoapySDR.
   202	- Whether the two coherent RX channels are better spent on Ku + L-band simultaneity, on two
   203	  Ku channels for OneWeb's alternating allocation, or on an interferometric baseline.
   204	- **Iridium STL (Satelles)** — a commercial receive-only GNSS-alternative PNT service on
