     1	# Design Baseline
     2	
     3	Status: **normative**
     4	Contract: v1 (2026-07-22)
     5	
     6	This is the single normative design document for the LEO signals-of-opportunity maritime
     7	PNT system. Every other project document, including `ARCHITECTURE.md`, is subordinate to
     8	this baseline. If another document conflicts with it, this document governs until this
     9	baseline is explicitly revised; superseded documents must be marked in their own text.
    10	
    11	## Mission and operating assumptions
    12	
    13	The system shall estimate position, velocity, heading, receiver clock bias and receiver
    14	clock drift on a moving, **manned displacement-hull vessel**, without GNSS, and provide a
    15	navigation solution to ArduPilot Rover in boat frame (`FRAME_CLASS=2`). A qualified person
    16	shall remain aboard with a physical, controller-independent manual override.
    17	
    18	The intended operating area is assumed to be the Danish straits. This is a **working
    19	assumption**, not a verified deployment decision. The displacement-hull assumption is also
    20	load-bearing: if the vessel planes or slams, the frequency-reference mounting and dynamics
    21	analysis shall be revisited.
    22	
    23	The system is both a research instrument and an operational navigator. It shall resolve
    24	that tension with one executable code path and one configuration key, `gnss_authority`:
    25	
    26	- `production`: GNSS measurements may enter fusion and are also journalled as truth.
    27	- `recorded_only`: GNSS measurements go only to the truth journal and never enter fusion.
    28	- `off`: GNSS is neither fused nor recorded as truth.
    29	- Any other value shall raise an error; it shall never fall back to `production`.
    30	
    31	Mode selection changes measurement authority, not implementation. The **aided** acceptance
    32	profile applies to `production`; the **denied** profile applies to `recorded_only` and
    33	`off`. Headline LEO performance statistics shall be computed offline from GNSS-withheld
    34	runs, never from a state estimate driven by GNSS.
    35	
    36	## Vessel equipment and sensor baseline
    37	
    38	The baseline sensor and interface set is:
    39	
    40	| Source | Required role | Baseline |
    41	|---|---|---|
    42	| Nuand bladeRF 2.0 micro xA4 or xA9 | Coherent RF sampling | Two coherent RX channels on one external reference. RX allocation is survey-dependent. |
    43	| Ku LNB and antenna | Starlink and conditional OneWeb reception | 10.7--12.75 GHz downconverted to approximately 950--2150 MHz IF. Track beacon/PSS-SSS correlation Doppler at 2.5--5 MHz bandwidth; do not depend on the degraded tone comb. |
    44	| L-band antenna | Iridium reception | Direct 1616--1626.5 MHz reception, bypassing the Ku LNB. |
    45	| 137 MHz antenna/front end and independent low-cost receiver | Orbcomm reception | A separate, non-coherent receiver provides continuous constellation/front-end diversity without consuming either bladeRF coherent RX channel; exact receiver is a BOM dependency `[UNVERIFIED]`. |
    46	| Free-running rubidium (FE-5680A class) or good OCXO | SDR frequency reference | 10 MHz external reference, calibrated only before deployment; no GNSS discipline. Mount its resultant acceleration-sensitivity vector vertically under the displacement-hull assumption. |
    47	| IMU | Propagation and turn dynamics | Drives every estimator propagation; it does not carry passage-scale position unaided. |
    48	| Two calibrated magnetometers | Heading measurement and redundancy | Calibration includes a propulsion-current deviation term. |
    49	| Speed log | Speed through water | Compared with LEO-derived speed over ground to estimate current set and drift. |
    50	| GNSS receiver | Aiding or truth, by explicit authority | Its path is controlled only by `gnss_authority`. |
    51	| Optional solar/sky-polarisation compass | Independent absolute heading | Candidate mitigation for magnetic heading weakness; not required until selected and verified. |
    52	| Companion computer monotonic clock | Runtime ordering and watchdogs | Time ownership is defined in the subordinate architecture. |
    53	| ArduPilot Rover autopilot | Navigation consumer | Receives MAVLink `GPS_INPUT` (message 232, `GPS1_TYPE=14`). |
    54	
    55	OneWeb tracker implementation is forbidden until a 24-hour channel-occupancy survey at the
    56	actual operating location demonstrates useful correlation gain. The survey shall decide
    57	whether the second coherent receiver is Ku + L-band (diverse simultaneous tracking) or
    58	dual Ku (alternating OneWeb channel coverage, with Iridium time-shared). Interferometric
    59	use remains an open research option and is not baseline functionality.
    60	
    61	Orbcomm shall remain simultaneous through its separate receiver in either bladeRF allocation.
    62	Its samples are not coherent with the bladeRF channels; this is intentional because it
    63	preserves both bladeRF channels and decorrelates receiver-clock and front-end failure modes.
    64	
    65	Ephemerides shall be cached CelesTrak supplemental ephemerides (SupGP), not plain TLEs,
    66	with an explicit age gate. The provisional maximum age shall be 6 hours, the first supplied
    67	error-growth datum (approximately 0.94 km orbit error), rather than one day or seven days;
    68	the mapping from orbit error to navigation integrity remains `[UNVERIFIED]`, so this limit
    69	shall be validated or tightened before steering trials.
