     8	
     9	## Decisions taken
    10	
    11	- **Authority is a continuously re-earned lease, not a latch.** Grant is the conjunction of
    12	  four conditions — human arm action (G1), solution integrity within the active profile's
    13	  protection limits (G2), calibration validity per the baseline extrinsics rule (G3),
    14	  watchdog liveness (G4) — evaluated entirely in the companion process upstream of MAVLink.
    15	  Logical AND: any single false term revokes.
    16	- **Separated three limit concepts** the brief and baseline risk conflating: acceptance
    17	  profile (campaign-grading trial statistics), protection limit (per-epoch authority gate),
    18	  active profile (aided/denied selected by `gnss_authority`). The baseline states acceptance
    19	  profiles do not replace per-epoch checks, so I defined the per-epoch protection limit as a
    20	  distinct, currently-[UNVERIFIED] number set, bounded no looser than the profile implies.
    21	- **Restated why the gate cannot live in ArduPilot** from the 100 m clamp: a censored 100 m
    22	  ceiling cannot distinguish a 5 m solution from a 5 km divergence, which is exactly the
    23	  discrimination G2 needs; plus ArduPilot cannot see LEO integrity state, companion liveness,
    24	  or the `gnss_authority` profile selection.
    25	- **Revocation semantics = stop steering + alarm + hand to helm, never a manoeuvre**, uniform
    26	  across all triggers, latched, requiring a fresh human arm action to re-grant (this also
    27	  answers authority-flapping). Two trigger classes (integrity/limit breach; lease expiry)
    28	  collapse to one action. Mapped every baseline degradation row to its authority effect.
    29	- **Backstop is three layered, and the software terminal state is deliberately non-kinetic.**
    30	  Layer 1 monotonic watchdog (lease renewed only by a fresh, integrity-passing, sequence-
    31	  advancing solution → authority cannot outlive the solution; `t_lease` constrained shorter
    32	  than ArduPilot's 4000 ms `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` so the companion always revokes before ArduPilot
    33	  could fire its own failsafe). Layer 2 escalation ladder S0→S3 with a terminal
    34	  latched-revoked + max-alarm state that performs no motion. Layer 3 physical helm override +
    35	  kill-cord, controller-independent.
    36	- **Hazard table** covers all seven brief-mandated hazards plus a supporting frequency-
    37	  reference/heel + heading-loss row, each as hazard → cause → mitigation → residual.
    38	- Marked the document **subordinate to DESIGN_BASELINE.md** in its header and body, as
    39	  required.
    40	
    41	## Key safety-design judgements (rationale)
    42	
    43	- **The "stop" that is safe is a non-manoeuvre.** The core inversion (failure mode 9) is that
    44	  a manned fast boat's surprise auto-manoeuvre is itself the hazard, so the software terminal
    45	  state on human non-response must be alarm, not motion; the boat holds its last physical
    46	  control state (least-surprising) until the helm or the kill-cord acts.
    47	- **`t_lease` < `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS`** is the load-bearing timing constraint that keeps ArduPilot
    48	  from ever being the first responder to solution loss; without it, a GPS-timeout failsafe
    49	  could manoeuvre before the companion revokes.
    50	- **Freshness must mean advance + integrity-pass, not mere output**, or a frozen estimator
    51	  renews its own lease (hazard H4). Flagged that sequence-freshness alone is insufficient if a
    52	  bug re-emits stale-but-advancing frames; a content-liveness check is the residual closer.
    53	
    54	## Assumptions
    55	
    56	- Manned displacement-hull vessel, Danish straits (working assumption), qualified helm aboard
    57	  with physical controller-independent override — all carried from the baseline.
    58	- The MAVLink `GPS_INPUT` / `GPS1_TYPE=14` interface named by the baseline is the actuation
    59	  boundary; field encodings and ArduPilot parameter names are subordinate v2/config work.
    60	- The displacement-hull vs "manned fast boat" wording gap (baseline vs handoff failure mode 9)
    61	  is reconciled by making the revocation *principle* speed-independent and all *timing* budgets
    62	  speed-dependent estimates that must be re-derived if the hull planes.
    63	
    64	## Open uncertainties ([UNVERIFIED], must be frozen before steering trials)
    65	
    66	- Per-epoch protection-limit numbers (position/velocity/heading, aided and denied) — the
    67	  baseline supplies acceptance-profile statistics but no per-epoch gate values.
    68	- `t_lease` (bounded < 4000 ms), `T_ack`, caution-band hysteresis thresholds and re-grant dwell.
    69	- ArduPilot GPS/EKF failsafe parameter values proving `GPS_INPUT` loss cannot auto-manoeuvre;
    70	  SITL-validated against pinned firmware commit + artifact checksum.
    71	- Whether MAVLink signing is available on the pinned firmware for the companion link.
    72	- The exact MAVLink-boundary mechanism of "stop steering" (mode command vs fix-validity
    73	  degrade) that hands control to the helm without provoking an ArduPilot failsafe manoeuvre.
    74	- Content-liveness (not just sequence-freshness) check to fully close hazard H4.
    75	- The irreducible H7 residual (human incapacitated at the helm, kill-cord unpulled) needs an
    76	  operational control (second crew / helm dead-man), out of software scope.
    77	
