     1	# Design Baseline
     2	
     3	Status: **normative**
     4	Contract: v1 (2026-07-22)
     5	
     6	This is the single normative design document for the LEO signals-of-opportunity maritime
     7	PNT system. Every other project document, including `ARCHITECTURE.md`, is subordinate to
     8	this baseline. If another document conflicts with it, this document governs until this
     9	baseline is explicitly revised; superseded documents must be marked in their own text.
    10	
    11	## Mission and operating assumptions
    12	
    13	The system shall estimate position, velocity, heading, receiver clock bias and receiver
    14	clock drift on a moving, **manned displacement-hull vessel**, without GNSS, and provide a
    15	navigation solution to ArduPilot Rover in boat frame (`FRAME_CLASS=2`). A qualified person
    16	shall remain aboard with a physical, controller-independent manual override.
    17	
    18	The intended operating area is assumed to be the Danish straits. This is a **working
    19	assumption**, not a verified deployment decision. The displacement-hull assumption is also
    20	load-bearing: if the vessel planes or slams, the frequency-reference mounting and dynamics
    21	analysis shall be revisited.
    22	
    23	The system is both a research instrument and an operational navigator. It shall resolve
    24	that tension with one executable code path and one configuration key, `gnss_authority`:
    25	
    26	- `production`: GNSS measurements may enter fusion and are also journalled as truth.
    27	- `recorded_only`: GNSS measurements go only to the truth journal and never enter fusion.
    28	- `off`: GNSS is neither fused nor recorded as truth.
    29	- Any other value shall raise an error; it shall never fall back to `production`.
    30	
    31	Mode selection changes measurement authority, not implementation. The **aided** acceptance
    32	profile applies to `production`; the **denied** profile applies to `recorded_only` and
    33	`off`. Headline LEO performance statistics shall be computed offline from GNSS-withheld
    34	runs, never from a state estimate driven by GNSS.
    35	
    36	## Vessel equipment and sensor baseline
    37	
    38	The baseline sensor and interface set is:
    39	
    40	| Source | Required role | Baseline |
    41	|---|---|---|
    42	| Nuand bladeRF 2.0 micro xA4 or xA9 | Coherent RF sampling | Two coherent RX channels on one external reference. RX allocation is survey-dependent. |
    43	| Ku LNB and antenna | Starlink and conditional OneWeb reception | 10.7--12.75 GHz downconverted to approximately 950--2150 MHz IF. Track beacon/PSS-SSS correlation Doppler at 2.5--5 MHz bandwidth; do not depend on the degraded tone comb. |
    44	| L-band antenna | Iridium reception | Direct 1616--1626.5 MHz reception, bypassing the Ku LNB. |
    45	| 137 MHz antenna/front end and independent low-cost receiver | Orbcomm reception | A separate, non-coherent receiver provides continuous constellation/front-end diversity without consuming either bladeRF coherent RX channel; exact receiver is a BOM dependency `[UNVERIFIED]`. |
    46	| Free-running rubidium (FE-5680A class) or good OCXO | SDR frequency reference | 10 MHz external reference, calibrated only before deployment; no GNSS discipline. Mount its resultant acceleration-sensitivity vector vertically under the displacement-hull assumption. |
    47	| IMU | Propagation and turn dynamics | Drives every estimator propagation; it does not carry passage-scale position unaided. |
    48	| Two calibrated magnetometers | Heading measurement and redundancy | Calibration includes a propulsion-current deviation term. |
    49	| Speed log | Speed through water | Compared with LEO-derived speed over ground to estimate current set and drift. |
    50	| GNSS receiver | Aiding or truth, by explicit authority | Its path is controlled only by `gnss_authority`. |
    51	| Optional solar/sky-polarisation compass | Independent absolute heading | Candidate mitigation for magnetic heading weakness; not required until selected and verified. |
    52	| Companion computer monotonic clock | Runtime ordering and watchdogs | Time ownership is defined in the subordinate architecture. |
    53	| ArduPilot Rover autopilot | Navigation consumer | Receives MAVLink `GPS_INPUT` (message 232, `GPS1_TYPE=14`). |
    54	
    55	OneWeb tracker implementation is forbidden until a 24-hour channel-occupancy survey at the
    56	actual operating location demonstrates useful correlation gain. The survey shall decide
    57	whether the second coherent receiver is Ku + L-band (diverse simultaneous tracking) or
    58	dual Ku (alternating OneWeb channel coverage, with Iridium time-shared). Interferometric
    59	use remains an open research option and is not baseline functionality.
    60	
    61	Orbcomm shall remain simultaneous through its separate receiver in either bladeRF allocation.
    62	Its samples are not coherent with the bladeRF channels; this is intentional because it
    63	preserves both bladeRF channels and decorrelates receiver-clock and front-end failure modes.
    64	
    65	Ephemerides shall be cached CelesTrak supplemental ephemerides (SupGP), not plain TLEs,
    66	with an explicit age gate. The provisional maximum age shall be 6 hours, the first supplied
    67	error-growth datum (approximately 0.94 km orbit error), rather than one day or seven days;
    68	the mapping from orbit error to navigation integrity remains `[UNVERIFIED]`, so this limit
    69	shall be validated or tightened before steering trials.
    70	
    71	## Rate contract
    72	
    73	All rates below are interface contracts. Values absent from the handoff are deliberately
    74	marked **estimate** and shall be validated against sensor capability and replay data.
    75	
    76	| Interface | Required rate/behaviour |
    77	|---|---|
    78	| SDR sample stream | Tracker-selected 2.5--5 MHz processing bandwidth per active correlation channel (stated expectation; sample rate itself remains `[UNVERIFIED]`). |
    79	| IMU to fusion executive | 100 Hz nominal (**estimate**), with every accepted sample causing time propagation; measurement arrivals shall never be the sole trigger for propagation. |
    80	| Dual magnetometers to fusion executive | 10 Hz each nominal (**estimate**). |
    81	| Speed log to fusion executive | 5 Hz nominal (**estimate**). |
    82	| LEO Doppler observations | Event-driven at each valid correlation solution; target 1 Hz per tracked signal (**estimate**). No synthetic observation is emitted to satisfy a rate. |
    83	| GNSS measurement/truth input | Native receiver rate, at least 1 Hz (**estimate**); routing is determined before fusion by `gnss_authority`. |
    84	| Navigation/integrity solution | 5 Hz nominal (**estimate**), using propagated dead-reckoned fill between absolute observations. |
    85	| MAVLink `GPS_INPUT` output | 5 Hz nominal (handoff requirement: approximately 5 Hz), continuously while the process is healthy, subject to steering-authority gating. |
    86	| Journal writes | Every input, decision and output event, preserving native rate; batched disk flush is allowed only if crash-loss bounds are explicitly configured (**estimate**). |
    87	
    88	The four-second `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` motivates continuous output but does not define estimator
    89	validity. Any dead-reckoning timeout shall govern **steering authority only**. It shall never
    90	stop propagation, observation processing, journalling, or the 10--20 minute position
    91	convergence process.
    92	
    93	## Estimator and degradation contract
    94	
    95	LEO Doppler shall be treated primarily as a velocity/range-rate observation. Position is
    96	recovered through the evolution of line-of-sight geometry over 10--20 minute,
    97	constant-heading legs, and manoeuvres reset convergence expectations. The estimator shall
    98	carry only states with implemented measurement paths. At minimum these are position,
    99	horizontal velocity, attitude/heading, receiver clock bias and receiver clock drift;
   100	position is 3-D with the vertical component constrained as specified below, and vertical
   101	velocity is not a baseline state. Additional
   102	states may be enabled only with a documented direct or cross-covariance measurement path;
   103	this permits observable IMU bias states but forbids decorative unobservable states.
   104	
   105	The normative LEO observable at the estimator interface is **correlation-peak Doppler**
   106	from the beacon/PSS-SSS tracker, converted to range rate with its stated nominal carrier;
   107	raw carrier-frequency Doppler is not the interface observable. Each satellite pass shall
   108	have a separate transmit-frequency nuisance-bias state, constant over the pass with a
   109	validated small random-walk model, so a satellite oscillator/carrier offset cannot be
   110	misinterpreted as receiver velocity or clock drift. The state shall be retired at pass end.
   111	
   112	The online estimator shall not carry a water-current state in the baseline. The solution
   113	module shall derive and journal the horizontal current vector as LEO-derived velocity over
   114	ground minus the heading-rotated speed-log velocity through water, with covariance
   115	propagated from both inputs. This makes current observable without enlarging the core state;
   116	a future first-class current state requires an explicit update model and baseline revision.
   117	
   118	Altitude shall be a vertical position state constrained to local mean sea level by a
   119	sea-surface pseudo-measurement. Its variance shall cover chart/geoid uncertainty plus local
   120	tide, wave and vessel-motion scale; the numeric model is `[UNVERIFIED]` and shall be frozen
   121	for the operating area before steering trials. Vertical velocity is excluded from steering
   122	use: `GPS_INPUT.alt` shall publish the MSL-constrained estimate, `vd` shall be 0, and
   123	`vert_accuracy` shall report a bound consistent with that pseudo-measurement rather than 0
   124	or an unconstrained filter covariance.
   125	
   126	The antenna phase centres, IMU origin and vessel reference point, including their full
   127	3-D lever arms and orientations, shall be surveyed calibration inputs. Doppler and inertial
   128	updates shall compensate rotational lever-arm velocity before fusion. Every affected
   129	measurement envelope shall reference the calibration ID for these extrinsics; missing or
   130	mismatched calibration is an integrity fault that forbids steering authority.
   131	
   132	Expected degradation is explicit:
   133	
   134	| Loss or condition | What remains / required response |
   135	|---|---|
   136	| GNSS absent or forbidden | Normal denied operation: IMU propagation, measured heading, speed-through-water and accepted LEO Doppler remain. GNSS cannot quietly re-enter fusion. |
   137	| One LEO constellation or RF front end lost | Continue with remaining accepted constellations and inertial/marine sensors; geometry and uncertainty shall degrade honestly. Loss of Ku shall not remove independently received Orbcomm, and loss of the LNB shall not remove direct L-band reception when the bladeRF allocation includes it. |
   138	| All LEO observations lost | Continue IMU propagation plus magnetometer and speed-log updates; covariance grows and current/ground-speed observability degrades. Steering authority expires by the independently enforced authority policy, but the estimator keeps running. |
   139	| One magnetometer lost/rejected | Continue with the other calibrated magnetometer, IMU turn dynamics and any selected non-magnetic heading sensor; inflate heading uncertainty. |
   140	| Both magnetometers lost/rejected | Continue short-term attitude propagation and any selected non-magnetic heading measurement. Heading is not passage-capable by inertial integration alone; revoke authority when its bound is exceeded. |
   141	| Speed log lost | LEO ground velocity and heading/IMU remain; direct water-current separation is unavailable and uncertainty shall reflect it. |
   142	| IMU stream stale | Time propagation is no longer trustworthy. The supervisor shall revoke steering authority; the estimator shall remain running but shall not fabricate propagation samples, and journalling and recovery may continue. |
   143	| Frequency reference degrades or sustained heel invalidates its model | Clock bias/drift states may absorb only modelled behaviour. Reject biased Doppler as integrity dictates and revoke authority when solution limits are exceeded. |
   144	| Sea-surface multipath biases a tracker | Correlation quality and innovation consistency shall drive rejection or uncertainty inflation; persistent constellation-correlated residuals revoke authority when protection limits are exceeded. |
   145	| Ephemeris missing or too old | Do not form or accept the affected Doppler prediction. Continue with other measurements; never bypass the age gate. |
   146	| Companion process stalls | Its independent monotonic watchdog shall make steering authority expire. Alarm escalation and the physical override remain available; software shall not autonomously select RTL, Loiter or disarm. |
   147	
   148	## Acceptance profiles
   149	
   150	These are system-level trial limits, evaluated against an independent truth journal over
   151	declared test segments. They do not replace per-epoch integrity and authority checks.
   152	Velocity means horizontal per-axis error; position means horizontal error. Exact percentile,
   153	window and confidence definitions remain `[UNVERIFIED]` and must be frozen before trials.
   154	
   155	| Criterion | Aided (`production`) | Denied (`recorded_only` or `off`) |
   156	|---|---:|---:|
   157	| Horizontal position error | <= 25 m (**estimate**, operational-grade target inferred from the handoff's example of a correct operational limit) | <= 200 m after an uninterrupted 20-minute constant-heading convergence leg (**estimate**, conservative edge of the stated approximately 100--200 m expectation) |
   158	| Horizontal velocity error, each axis | <= 0.02 m/s (**estimate**, operational target within the handoff's 0.007--0.04 m/s expectation) | <= 0.04 m/s (**estimate**, upper edge of the stated 0.7--4 cm/s expectation) |
   159	| Heading error | <= 2 degrees (**estimate**) | <= 5 degrees (**estimate**) |
   160	| Horizontal current-vector error | Recorded and scored, but no pass/fail threshold until local truth instrumentation and current variability are characterised (`[UNVERIFIED]`) | Same; omission of a threshold does not make publication optional |
   161	| Output continuity | Valid `GPS_INPUT` at nominal 5 Hz while healthy; no gap >= 4 s (**estimate** derived from the stated timeout) | Same; dead-reckoned fill is explicitly permitted, with reported uncertainty and authority enforced upstream |
   162	| GNSS isolation | GNSS fusion is allowed and auditable | Zero GNSS measurements delivered to fusion; `recorded_only` may write truth only |
   163	| Replay determinism | Same raw log, config, software and deterministic execution settings produces bit-exact journal outputs; explicitly non-deterministic backends require a frozen numeric tolerance `[UNVERIFIED]` | Same, including a paired GNSS-withheld replay used for headline results |
   164	
   165	The aided numbers are engineering estimates, not literature-derived guarantees. Here,
   166	“operational-grade” means satisfying the estimated 25 m position, 0.02 m/s per-axis
   167	velocity, and 2 degree heading trial targets while integrity permits steering. It does not
   168	mean certified safety performance. The denied limit intentionally does not inherit the
   169	aided 25 m position target, which would make the research result fail by construction.
   170	The 2/5 degree heading gates are provisional engineering targets chosen to bound transverse
   171	velocity error from heading-rotated speed-log measurements while allowing degraded magnetic
   172	operation; the handoff supplies no validated heading limit, so both require trial validation
   173	and are `[UNVERIFIED]`.
   174	
   175	The real horizontal and speed uncertainty monitor and every steering gate shall live in
   176	the companion process upstream of MAVLink, because the handoff states that ArduPilot
   177	internally clamps reported horizontal accuracy at 100 m. Report `horiz_accuracy` and
   178	`speed_accuracy` independently in `GPS_INPUT`. Publish fused heading through the
   179	`GPS_INPUT.yaw` field with its validity governed by the companion integrity gate. `ODOMETRY`
   180	shall not be used for this navigation injection because its ArduPilot path cannot transport
   181	the required per-epoch velocity uncertainty.
   182	
   183	## Verification obligations
   184	
   185	Before steering trials, tests shall demonstrate end-to-end execution from real-capture
   186	replay through propagation, measurement updates, integrity, authority decision and
   187	`GPS_INPUT`. Jacobians shall be checked against finite differences. The same raw log shall
   188	be replayed aided and GNSS-withheld. MAVLink integration shall be checked in ArduPilot SITL
   189	against a pinned firmware commit and artifact checksum. Measurements, inferences and
   190	estimates shall remain distinguishable in resulting evidence.
     1	# Architecture
     2	
     3	Status: subordinate to [`DESIGN_BASELINE.md`](DESIGN_BASELINE.md)
     4	Contract: v1 (2026-07-22)
     5	
     6	`DESIGN_BASELINE.md` is the single normative design document. This architecture implements
     7	it and is subordinate wherever the two differ.
     8	
     9	## Runtime shape and module boundaries
    10	
    11	The **fusion executive** is the first runnable vertical slice and the only orchestrator.
    12	It owns the main event loop and connects these bounded modules through typed interfaces:
    13	
    14	1. **Configuration and authority** parses configuration, rejects an unknown
    15	   `gnss_authority`, and constructs the single common processing graph. It applies GNSS
    16	   routing before any fusion update.
    17	2. **Clock/time service** owns runtime time (defined below), timestamps ingress, estimates
    18	   UTC mapping and exposes monotonic deadlines.
    19	3. **Sensor adapters** convert IMU, magnetometer, speed-log and GNSS device records into
    20	   bus measurements without estimation policy. The Orbcomm adapter consumes a separate,
    21	   non-coherent low-cost receiver and does not consume a bladeRF coherent RX channel.
    22	4. **SDR capture** configures coherent channels and records raw IQ plus capture metadata.
    23	   It does not decide whether a signal is navigation-safe.
    24	5. **Signal trackers** turn IQ into Doppler/range-rate candidates with uncertainty and
    25	   quality metadata. Starlink uses beacon/PSS-SSS correlation; OneWeb remains disabled
    26	   until its required survey gate passes. Constellation trackers share an observation
    27	   interface, not hidden state. Their estimator-facing observable is correlation-peak
    28	   Doppler, never an unspecified raw carrier estimate.
    29	6. **Ephemeris store and propagator** validates SupGP identity and age, then produces
    30	   satellite position and velocity at observation time.
    31	7. **Doppler predictor** combines propagated satellite state, receiver state and clock
    32	   model to predict a range-rate/Doppler observation and its linearisation.
    33	8. **Observation integrity gate** compares a tracker observation with a real predictor
    34	   output, recording accept/reject and rationale. It cannot exist as a functional gate
    35	   before modules 6 and 7.
    36	9. **Estimator** propagates on every IMU event and applies only accepted, implemented
    37	   updates. Its state registry requires a direct or cross-covariance measurement path for
    38	   every declared state. It creates one per-satellite, per-pass transmit-frequency nuisance
    39	   bias with a small validated random walk and retires it when the pass ends. It also applies
    40	   the MSL sea-surface altitude pseudo-measurement; water current is derived downstream and
    41	   is not a baseline estimator state.
    42	10. **Solution integrity monitor** derives protection/uncertainty metrics independently
    43	    of ArduPilot's censored accuracy view.
    44	11. **Authority supervisor** grants or revokes steering authority from solution health,
    45	    freshness and uncertainty. Its monotonic watchdog is independent of estimator
    46	    convergence; expiry cannot stop the estimator. It raises and escalates alarms but does
    47	    not select RTL, Loiter or disarm.
    48	12. **MAVLink publisher** emits approximately 5 Hz `GPS_INPUT`, with independent horizontal
    49	    and speed accuracy, using propagated fill between absolute updates. It publishes fused
    50	    heading in `yaw`, the MSL-constrained altitude in `alt`, vertical velocity `vd = 0`, and
    51	    a `vert_accuracy` consistent with the sea-surface constraint; it does not publish
    52	    `ODOMETRY` as the navigation injection.
    53	13. **Journal/replay service** writes measurements, truth and decisions and can reproduce
    54	    the same bus stream from disk. Offline evaluation consumes journals; it does not feed
    55	    results back into online rejection.
    56	
    57	No leaf module communicates directly with another leaf module. It publishes to or is
    58	called by the executive through explicit ports, which makes the connected running path the
    59	unit of integration rather than a collection of independently tested parts.
    60	
    61	## Measurement bus
    62	
    63	The measurement bus is an in-process, bounded, typed event stream owned and drained by the
    64	fusion executive. Producers submit immutable envelopes; one executive orders, journals and
    65	dispatches them. Backpressure and overflow are explicit health events, never silent drops.
    66	
    67	Every envelope contains: schema version, source ID, sequence number, measurement kind,
    68	source/sample time, host receive monotonic time, optional UTC time plus its uncertainty,
    69	payload SI units and frame identifier, covariance/uncertainty, quality flags, calibration
    70	ID and provenance linking it to a capture or source record. The calibration ID shall resolve
    71	the surveyed antenna phase-centre, IMU and vessel-reference extrinsics; Doppler and inertial
    72	updates compensate rotational lever-arm velocity, and a missing/mismatched ID is an
    73	authority-blocking integrity event. Exact field encoding and frame
    74	enumeration are v2 contract work; the concepts are binding here.
    75	
    76	Ordering uses host monotonic receive time with per-source sequence checks. Measurement time
    77	is retained for delayed updates. Clock resets, sequence gaps, lateness and queue overflow
    78	become journalled integrity events. The bus carries at least IMU, heading, speed-through-
    79	water, GNSS, tracker Doppler, ephemeris state, predicted Doppler, gate decision, estimator
    80	solution, integrity status, authority status and output status messages.
    81	
    82	GNSS routing is enforced at bus ingress: `production` permits a fusion copy and truth copy;
    83	`recorded_only` permits only the truth-journal route; `off` permits neither. There is no
    84	downstream switch that can accidentally re-authorise it.
    85	
    86	## Time ownership
    87	
    88	The **clock/time service is the sole owner of time**. Device adapters may report device
    89	counters or UTC labels, but may not define ordering, freshness or deadlines. At process
    90	start the service establishes a host-monotonic epoch; all runtime ordering, stale-data
    91	checks, authority leases and watchdogs use that monotonic domain. It also maintains an
    92	explicit, uncertainty-bearing mapping between device time, host monotonic time and UTC for
    93	ephemeris evaluation and logs. The estimator owns receiver clock bias and drift **states**,
    94	not system time. GNSS UTC, when present, is a measurement and never silently disciplines
    95	the SDR reference or runtime clock.
    96	
    97	All persistent timestamps include monotonic nanoseconds from the run epoch and, when
    98	available, UTC as an absolute RFC 3339 timestamp. The clock model and its uncertainty are
    99	journalled so replay can reconstruct event timing. Nanosecond representation and RFC 3339
   100	encoding are architecture choices (**estimates**) pending v2 schema review.
   101	
   102	## On-disk formats
   103	
   104	All formats are append-only and versioned. A run directory has a manifest containing run
   105	UUID, schema versions, absolute UTC creation time when available, monotonic epoch metadata,
   106	configuration hash, calibration IDs, software revision, hardware/channel setup, ephemeris
   107	snapshot identity and file hashes. Atomic segment finalisation and recovery after an
   108	unclean stop are required; specific container encodings are `[UNVERIFIED]` pending v2.
   109	
   110	### Raw IQ capture
   111	
   112	IQ is stored in independently recoverable, fixed-duration segments. Each segment contains
   113	interleaved coherent RX-channel samples without lossy compression plus a sidecar/header
   114	with sample representation, endianness, sample rate, centre frequency, bandwidth, gain,
   115	channel allocation, external-reference status, first-sample monotonic and optional UTC
   116	time, sample count, overrun/gap records and calibration/configuration identity. Raw ADC
   117	packing versus normalised signed-integer representation is `[UNVERIFIED]`.
   118	
   119	### Measurement journal
   120	
   121	The measurement journal is a length-delimited binary stream of the exact versioned bus
   122	envelopes presented to and produced by the executive. Records carry checksums; segments
   123	carry indexes by monotonic time, source and message kind. It includes raw sensor records,
   124	tracker observations, ephemeris products, predictions, accept/reject decisions,
   125	propagations, updates, solutions, integrity and authority transitions, alarms and MAVLink
   126	publication outcomes, including derived horizontal current vectors and their propagated
   127	covariance. A replay reader shall preserve values and event ordering and shall
   128	reject unknown required schema versions rather than guess. The binary codec is
   129	`[UNVERIFIED]`.
   130	
   131	### Truth journal
   132	
   133	The truth journal is physically and logically separate from the measurement journal. It
   134	uses a versioned, length-delimited record model with source ID, source/sample time, host
   135	monotonic receipt time, optional UTC, position/velocity/heading truth payload, covariance,
   136	quality and provenance. In `recorded_only`, GNSS can write here but there is no truth-to-bus
   137	fusion edge. Permissions/API boundaries shall prevent the online estimator and reject gate
   138	from reading it. Offline evaluation aligns truth after the run and computes aided versus
   139	withheld results. Codec and access-control mechanism are `[UNVERIFIED]`.
   140	
   141	## Build and verification order
   142	
   143	Development proceeds as connected vertical slices:
   144	
   145	1. Build a minimal fusion executive with clock service, bounded bus, journals/replay, one
   146	   IMU propagation path, solution output and observable end-to-end integration test.
   147	2. Add configuration/authority routing and prove that `recorded_only` has no fusion edge
   148	   and unknown values fail.
   149	3. Add each marine sensor as adapter, journal record and actual estimator update; do not add
   150	   a filter state before its update path exists.
   151	4. Add ephemeris store/propagator, then Doppler predictor, with numeric finite-difference
   152	   checks for applicable Jacobians.
   153	5. Add capture and one tracker path through replay into predictor and estimator.
   154	6. Only now add the observation reject gate, because it has a real prediction producer.
   155	7. Add integrity, independent monotonic authority watchdog and 5 Hz MAVLink publisher;
   156	   verify that authority expiry never stops estimator execution.
   157	8. Expand constellations and receiver allocation only behind their evidence gates.
   158	9. Prove identical captures through paired aided and GNSS-withheld replay, then validate
   159	   MAVLink against pinned ArduPilot SITL with commit hash and artifact checksum.
   160	
   161	Every slice must demonstrate that the running estimator propagates from IMU input even
   162	when no measurements update it. Unit success without an executable end-to-end path is not
   163	completion.
