    32	`.orchestration/reports/U-S1.md`: decisions taken, assumptions, open uncertainties, contract version.
     1	# Safety Case
     2	
     3	Status: **subordinate to [`DESIGN_BASELINE.md`](DESIGN_BASELINE.md)**
     4	Contract: v1 (2026-07-22)
     5	
     6	`DESIGN_BASELINE.md` is the single normative design document. This safety case implements
     7	and is bounded by it. Where the two differ, the baseline governs until the baseline is
     8	explicitly revised. This document adds no new sensor, estimator or acceptance requirement;
     9	it specifies **how steering authority is granted, revoked and backstopped**, deliverable 6
    10	of `docs/HANDOFF_PROMPT_BLADERF.md`, and it draws every degradation trigger from the
    11	baseline's degradation contract.
    12	
    13	Values that the baseline and handoff do not supply — protection-limit numbers, alarm and
    14	lease timings, failsafe parameter values — are marked **[UNVERIFIED]** or **estimate** and
    15	must be frozen before steering trials. They are engineering placeholders, not certified
    16	safety performance.
    17	
    18	---
    19	
    20	## 0. Terms, and the three things this case keeps separate
    21	
    22	Three limit concepts are deliberately distinct and must not be conflated:
    23	
    24	- **Acceptance profile** (baseline §Acceptance profiles): system-level trial statistics
    25	  (for example ≤ 25 m aided, ≤ 200 m denied horizontal position) computed offline over
    26	  declared test segments against the truth journal. These grade the *campaign*. The baseline
    27	  states they **do not replace per-epoch integrity and authority checks**.
    28	- **Protection limit**: the per-epoch bound the authority supervisor tests each solution
    29	  against, derived by the solution integrity monitor (architecture module 10) from the
    30	  filter covariance and integrity state, *independently of ArduPilot*. The baseline does not
    31	  supply protection-limit numbers; they are **[UNVERIFIED]** and shall be no looser than the
    32	  active acceptance profile implies.
    33	- **Active profile**: which limit set applies, selected by `gnss_authority` — the **aided**
    34	  profile under `production`, the **denied** profile under `recorded_only` and `off`. The
    35	  selection follows the baseline's mode rule and never changes code path.
    36	
    37	Two further terms:
    38	
    39	- **Authority** is the companion process's assertion of autonomous steering: whether the
    40	  fused solution is permitted to steer the vessel via `GPS_INPUT`. It is a *lease*, not a
    41	  latch — it must be actively and continuously re-earned.
    42	- **The helm** is the qualified person aboard (baseline: a qualified person shall remain
    43	  aboard with a physical, controller-independent manual override). The helm is the primary
    44	  safety actor. Software is subordinate to the helm at all times.
    45	
    46	**Vessel-speed caveat.** The baseline vessel is a **displacement-hull** vessel operating
    47	provisionally in the Danish straits; handoff failure mode 9 frames the hazard as a *manned
    48	fast boat*. The revocation principle below (revocation is never itself a manoeuvre) holds at
    49	any speed. The *timing* budgets (lease deadline, acknowledgement window) are sized to the
    50	vessel's manoeuvre/collision time budget, which shrinks as speed rises. All timing values
    51	here are conservative estimates for a displacement hull and are **[UNVERIFIED]**; if the
    52	hull planes or slams they shall be re-derived, consistent with the baseline's load-bearing
    53	displacement-hull assumption.
    54	
    55	---
    56	
    57	## 1. What grants steering authority
    58	
    59	Steering authority is granted **only while the full conjunction below holds**. It is a
    60	logical AND: any single false term revokes authority (§2). The companion never self-grants;
    61	grant is opt-in by the helm and continuously re-earned by the solution.
    62	
    63	| # | Grant condition (all must hold) | Testable predicate | Evaluated in |
    64	|---|---|---|---|
    65	| G1 | **Human arm action** | The helm has performed a positive, explicit companion-steering arm action, and it has not since been withdrawn. Absence of arm ⇒ no authority; this is the default state at process start. | Companion (authority supervisor, module 11) |
    66	| G2 | **Solution integrity within the active profile's protection limits** | Horizontal-position, horizontal-velocity and heading protection limits derived by the integrity monitor are each within the active-profile limit set, evaluated per epoch on the true (unclamped) covariance. | Companion (integrity monitor module 10 → supervisor module 11) |
    67	| G3 | **Calibration validity (baseline extrinsics rule)** | Every measurement feeding the current solution carries a calibration ID that resolves the surveyed antenna-phase-centre / IMU / vessel-reference extrinsics; none is missing or mismatched; the frequency-reference pre-deployment calibration is present and unexpired. Missing/mismatched calibration is an integrity fault. | Companion (bus ingress + integrity monitor) |
    68	| G4 | **Watchdog liveness** | The supervisor's monotonic authority lease is unexpired, i.e. it has been renewed by a *fresh, integrity-passing* solution within the lease deadline, on the clock service's monotonic domain (architecture §Time ownership). | Companion (supervisor monotonic watchdog) |
    69	
    70	Freshness in G4 means the solution's own timestamp/sequence has advanced *and* the solution
    71	passed G2/G3 this epoch. A frozen or stalled output does not renew the lease (see hazard H4).
    72	
    73	### Why the authority gate cannot live in ArduPilot
    74	
    75	Every grant condition is evaluated **in the companion process, upstream of MAVLink**,
    76	because ArduPilot cannot see what the gate must test:
    77	
    78	- **The covariance ArduPilot exposes is censored.** The handoff and baseline state ArduPilot
    79	  clamps reported horizontal accuracy at **100 m** internally; its EKF variance is therefore
    80	  a *censored view*. A censored 100 m ceiling cannot distinguish a healthy 5 m solution from
    81	  a 5 km divergence — exactly the discrimination G2 requires. The real, unclamped protection
    82	  limit exists only upstream, so the gate must live upstream. This is not tunable away.
    83	- **ArduPilot has no visibility of the LEO-specific integrity state** (calibration-ID match,
    84	  ephemeris age, per-pass transmit-bias health, innovation consistency) that G2/G3 test.
    85	- **ArduPilot does not know the companion's liveness** (G4) — a stalled companion still
    86	  looks, from ArduPilot's side, like a GPS that has merely gone quiet.
    87	- **`gnss_authority` and the aided/denied profile selection are companion concepts.**
    88	  ArduPilot cannot select the active protection-limit set.
    89	
    90	Consequently ArduPilot is treated as a **downstream actuator that must never be relied on to
    91	judge navigation integrity**. Its own GPS/EKF failsafe actions are configured so that loss
    92	or degradation of the injected `GPS_INPUT` **cannot itself command an autonomous manoeuvre**
    93	(RTL/Loiter/disarm) — because such a manoeuvre is the hazard (§2). The specific ArduPilot
    94	failsafe parameter values are **[UNVERIFIED]** and are a SITL-validated configuration
    95	deliverable pinned to a firmware commit and artifact checksum (handoff verification
    96	discipline).
    97	
    98	---
    99	
   100	## 2. What revokes steering authority
   101	
   102	### 2.1 Revocation semantics on a manned vessel at speed
   103	
   104	Revocation is uniform regardless of cause and is **never a manoeuvre**:
   105	
   106	> **Revocation = stop steering + alarm + hand to helm.**
   107	
   108	Software shall **never** autonomously select RTL, Loiter or disarm (handoff failure mode 9;
   109	baseline degradation contract, final row). On a manned vessel making way, an *unannounced
   110	manoeuvre at speed is itself the hazard* — a surprise turn, stop or hold can put the vessel
   111	beam-on to sea, into traffic, or throw crew. Therefore:
   112	
   113	- **Stop steering** means the companion ceases to assert autonomous navigation control. It
   114	  does not command a course change. Control surfaces are left to the helm; ArduPilot is
   115	  commanded to (or held in) a manual/helm-controlled state rather than allowed to let a
   116	  GPS-timeout failsafe fire a surprise manoeuvre.
   117	- **Alarm** is raised to the helm immediately (§3.2 ladder).
   118	- **Hand to helm** — the qualified person takes manual control. The helm's physical override
   119	  mechanically dominates the autopilot at all times (baseline; §3.3).
   120	
   121	Revocation is **latched**: once revoked, authority is not re-granted automatically. Re-grant
   122	requires *all* of §1 true again **and** a fresh explicit human arm action (G1), after a
   123	stabilisation dwell. This is the primary defence against authority flapping (hazard H3).
   124	
   125	Two revocation trigger classes both produce this same action:
   126	
   127	- **Integrity/limit breach** — a grant condition (G2 or G3) becomes false: the solution is
   128	  too uncertain, or calibration/ephemeris integrity fails.
   129	- **Lease expiry** — G4 fails: no fresh integrity-passing solution renewed the lease within
   130	  its deadline (covers estimator stall, companion stall, thread death, output freeze).
   131	
   132	### 2.2 Revocation mapped to every baseline degradation row
   133	
   134	Each row of the baseline degradation contract is mapped to its authority effect. "Continue"
   135	means the estimator keeps running (baseline: authority expiry never stops the estimator) and
   136	authority persists **only while §1 still holds**.
   137	
   138	| Baseline degradation row | Authority supervisor response | Revocation trigger |
   139	|---|---|---|
   140	| GNSS absent or forbidden | Normal denied operation; **denied** protection-limit set active. Not itself a revocation. GNSS cannot re-enter fusion (enforced at bus ingress). | None (mode selection) |
   141	| One LEO constellation / RF front end lost | Continue; authority persists if protection limits still met; geometry/uncertainty degrade honestly. | G2 if protection limit breached |
   142	| **All LEO observations lost** | Estimator continues on IMU + magnetometer + speed log; covariance grows. Authority expires as the growing protection limit crosses threshold, or as the lease is no longer renewed by an in-limit solution. | G2, then G4 |
   143	| One magnetometer lost/rejected | Continue on the other calibrated magnetometer; inflate heading uncertainty. | G2 (heading limit) if breached |
   144	| **Both magnetometers lost/rejected** | Heading is not passage-capable by inertial integration alone; revoke when the heading protection bound is exceeded. | G2 (heading limit) |
   145	| Speed log lost | Continue; current separation unavailable; uncertainty reflects it. | G2 if breached |
   146	| **IMU stream stale** | Time propagation no longer trustworthy → supervisor revokes. Estimator stays running, does not fabricate propagation samples. | G2/G4 (stale-propagation integrity fault) |
   147	| Frequency reference degrades / sustained heel invalidates its model | Reject biased Doppler per integrity; revoke when solution limits exceeded. | G2 |
   148	| Sea-surface multipath biases a tracker | Correlation-quality / innovation-consistency rejection or inflation; persistent constellation-correlated residuals revoke when protection limits exceeded. | G2 |
   149	| Ephemeris missing or too old | Do not form/accept the affected Doppler prediction (never bypass the age gate). Continue on other measurements; revoke only if the surviving solution breaches limits. | G3 (age gate) → G2 |
   150	| Calibration ID missing/mismatched | Authority-blocking integrity fault (baseline extrinsics rule). | G3 |
   151	| **Companion process stalls** | Independent monotonic watchdog makes the lease expire → authority revoked. Alarm escalation and physical override remain. Software never selects RTL/Loiter/disarm. | G4 |
   152	
   153	The DR (dead-reckoning) timeout is one input to the G2/G4 logic. Per the baseline and
   154	handoff failure mode 3 it **governs authority only** — it never stops propagation,
   155	observation processing, journalling, or the 10–20 minute position-convergence process.
   156	
   157	---
   158	
   159	## 3. The backstop when the human does not respond
   160	
   161	Three layers, in order of who acts. Software's automatic layer only *stops asserting* and
   162	*alerts*; it never manoeuvres. The kinetic final layer is physical and controller-independent.
   163	
   164	### 3.1 Layer 1 — supervisor monotonic watchdog (automatic, so authority cannot outlive the solution)
   165	
   166	Authority is a **lease** on the clock service's monotonic domain (architecture §Time
   167	ownership), continuously renewed **only** by a fresh, in-limit, calibration-valid solution
   168	(G2+G3+G4). If renewal stops for *any* reason — solution unhealthy, integrity fault,
   169	estimator stall, thread death, whole-companion stall — the lease is not renewed, expires, and
   170	authority drops to revoked. This is what guarantees **authority cannot outlive the solution**
   171	(handoff failure mode 9).
   172	
   173	Independence properties (from the baseline/architecture, restated as safety requirements):
   174	
   175	- The watchdog is **independent of estimator convergence**: its expiry cannot stop the
   176	  estimator, and the estimator's slow convergence cannot hold the lease open.
   177	- The lease uses the monotonic clock, not device or UTC time, so a device clock reset or a
   178	  spoofed UTC label cannot extend it.
   179	- **Lease deadline `t_lease` shall be shorter than ArduPilot's `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (4000 ms)**
   180	  so the companion always revokes *before* ArduPilot's own GPS timeout could fire a failsafe.
   181	  Provisional `t_lease` on the order of a few hundred milliseconds to ~1 s (a small multiple
   182	  of the 5 Hz / 200 ms nominal solution interval) — **[UNVERIFIED] estimate**, frozen before
   183	  trials against the vessel manoeuvre budget.
   184	
   185	### 3.2 Layer 2 — un-acknowledged-alarm escalation ladder (human-in-the-loop)
   186	
   187	The ladder exists to *get the helm's attention*, not to substitute for the helm. Because
   188	software must never manoeuvre, **the terminal state is not kinetic**: it is a latched
   189	revocation plus maximal alarm, awaiting the human.
   190	
   191	| Stage | Entry condition | Authority | Annunciation | Exit / timing |
   192	|---|---|---|---|---|
   193	| **S0 NOMINAL** | All §1 conditions hold. | Granted | None. | → S1 when a metric enters the caution band. |
   194	| **S1 CAUTION** | A protection metric crosses a *caution* threshold set below the revoke threshold (hysteresis band), or a single sensor is lost with margin shrinking. | Granted (still) | Soft visual + audible pre-alert: "solution degrading, prepare to take the helm." | → S0 if metric recovers past the caution threshold; → S2 on any grant condition failing. |
   195	| **S2 WARNING (REVOKED)** | Any grant condition G1–G4 false. | **Revoked, latched.** Stop steering + hand to helm. | Loud alarm demanding acknowledgement. | Helm acknowledges within `T_ack` → S4; no acknowledgement within `T_ack` → S3. |
   196	| **S3 ESCALATED** | S2 un-acknowledged for `T_ack`. | Revoked, latched. | Maximal continuous alarm; secondary annunciators engaged (distinct tone; remote/repeater alert if fitted). | Helm acknowledges → S4. Otherwise **remains in S3 indefinitely** (terminal software state). |
   197	| **S4 LATCHED-SAFE (acknowledged)** | Helm acknowledged S2/S3. | Revoked, latched. | Steady fault indication. | Re-grant requires all §1 true **and** a fresh G1 arm action after a stabilisation dwell. No auto re-grant. |
   198	
   199	- `T_ack` (un-acknowledged escalation window): **[UNVERIFIED] estimate**, on the order of a
   200	  few seconds, sized to the vessel's manoeuvre/collision budget; shorter for a faster hull.
   201	- **Terminal state = S3 LATCHED-REVOKED + MAX ALARM.** Software performs **no** kinetic
   202	  action there. If the helm never responds, the vessel continues under its last physical
   203	  control state (rudder/throttle where the helm left them — the least-surprising outcome, no
   204	  unannounced manoeuvre) until the helm acts or the physical layer (§3.3) intervenes. This is
   205	  the deliberate resolution of the safety inversion: an unresponsive human must not trigger a
   206	  surprise manoeuvre, so the software's terminal behaviour is *alarm, not motion*.
   207	- Escalation is one-directional under fault: authority is never silently re-granted from any
   208	  alarm stage.
   209	
   210	### 3.3 Layer 3 — physical, controller-independent override (final layer, outside software)
   211	
   212	Two physical controls, both independent of the companion computer, ArduPilot and MAVLink,
   213	and therefore effective even if all of them are faulted:
   214	
   215	- **Helm manual override.** The qualified person's steering/throttle mechanically dominates
   216	  the autopilot's actuator at any time (baseline precondition). This is how "hand to helm"
   217	  becomes real motion control.
   218	- **Helm kill-cord.** A physical lanyard on the helm that cuts propulsion (handoff failure
   219	  mode 9: "a helm kill-cord is cheap and standard"). It fires if the helmsman is *displaced
   220	  from the helm* (overboard/incapacitated and the lanyard pulls out), stopping the engine
   221	  without any software involvement. It is the final backstop for the case where the sole
   222	  safety actor is displaced.
   223	
   224	Pre-trial checklist items (operational, not software): kill-cord clipped to the helmsman;
   225	manual override tested; ArduPilot non-manoeuvre failsafe configuration verified in SITL.
   226	
   227	---
   228	
   229	## 4. Hazard table
   230	
   231	hazard → cause → mitigation → residual risk. Residuals marked **[UNVERIFIED]** are bounded
   232	only after validation on GNSS-withheld replay against truth and/or SITL, per the handoff
   233	verification discipline.
   234	
   235	| # | Hazard | Cause | Mitigation | Residual risk |
   236	|---|---|---|---|---|
   237	| **H1** | **Stale-solution steering** — steering on an old/dead-reckoned solution whose true error has already grown past limits. | Absolute LEO fixes arrive minutes apart; DR fill between; covariance grows with motion. | Covariance is actually time-propagated from IMU every accepted sample (baseline; guards handoff failure modes 5); per-epoch protection-limit gate G2; lease G4 renewed only by a *fresh* in-limit solution; DR timeout governs authority only, `t_lease` < `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS`. | If the covariance *model itself* is optimistic (see H2), a fresh-looking solution can under-report staleness. Bounded by conservative process noise + the human backstop; magnitude **[UNVERIFIED]** until withheld-replay validation. |
   238	| **H2** | **Optimistic covariance (wrong-Jacobian class)** — filter reports a tight, wrong covariance; authority granted on false confidence. Most dangerous, because the gate *consumes* this covariance. | Wrong Jacobian (silent: filter still runs and produces a covariance — handoff explicitly), missing propagation, mis-modelled process noise. | Numerical Jacobian check vs finite differences before trials (handoff); independent innovation-consistency / NEES-style monitoring in the integrity monitor as a covariance-realism check that does not itself trust the covariance; conservative process noise; headline stats only from GNSS-withheld runs (no circular validation). | Consistency monitors have finite power; a slowly-biasing fault under the low LEO observation rate may evade detection between updates. Real, **[UNVERIFIED]**; bounded by conservative limits and the human backstop. |
   239	| **H3** | **Authority flapping** — grant/revoke toggling around a threshold, causing repeated stop-steering/hand-to-helm churn (itself a hazard: confuses the helm, injects control discontinuities). | Protection metric noise near the revoke threshold. | Hysteresis band (S1 caution threshold below the revoke threshold); **latched** revocation requiring explicit human re-arm — no automatic re-grant; stabilisation dwell before re-grant. | Mis-tuned hysteresis could still flap or be sluggish; band and dwell values **[UNVERIFIED]**, frozen before trials. |
   240	| **H4** | **Silent estimator halt vs authority-alive inversion** — estimator stalls / freezes its last output while authority stays granted → steering a frozen fix. | Estimator thread stall, deadlock, or frozen output that still "looks" valid. | Lease G4 renewed **only** by a solution whose timestamp/sequence advanced *and* passed integrity this epoch; a frozen output does not renew → watchdog expires (§3.1). Watchdog is on the independent monotonic clock. The safe half of the inversion (authority dead, estimator alive) is guaranteed by the baseline: watchdog expiry cannot stop the estimator. | If a stalled path re-emits a *stale-but-sequence-advancing* frame (bug), freshness alone would miss it; mitigated by content-change/innovation-liveness checks. Residual **[UNVERIFIED]**. |
   241	| **H5** | **MAVLink link loss mid-authority** — companion↔ArduPilot link drops while authority granted; risk that ArduPilot's own GPS timeout then fires a surprise failsafe. | Cable/USB/serial fault, connector at sea. | ArduPilot GPS/EKF failsafe pre-configured to **not** auto-manoeuvre on GPS loss (hold/hand-to-manual), SITL-validated; companion detects link loss and treats it as revocation; `t_lease` < `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (4000 ms) so the companion revokes first; helm override and kill-cord are link-independent. | An unavoidable window (up to ~4 s) where ArduPilot runs on the last `GPS_INPUT` before its own timeout. Bounded by that window + the non-manoeuvre failsafe config; exact params **[UNVERIFIED]** until SITL-verified. |
   242	| **H6** | **`GPS_INPUT` spoof / failure of the companion process itself** — a plausible-but-wrong `GPS_INPUT` reaches ArduPilot, from an internal companion fault or an external injection. | (a) Companion software fault/corruption. (b) Unauthenticated MAVLink link; physical access to it. | (a) Same integrity monitor + watchdog + withheld-replay validation; a corrupted solution failing integrity won't renew the lease. (b) Dedicated point-to-point companion↔autopilot link (not shared/networked); companion is the sole authorised source (`GPS1_TYPE=14`); enable MAVLink signing (**[UNVERIFIED]** whether supported on the pinned firmware — recommended). Note the LEO-SoOP premise removes the *RF* GNSS-spoof surface (no GPS to spoof); the MAVLink injection surface remains. | A companion fault that is simultaneously wrong *and* integrity-consistent (correlated fault) is the hard residual; bounded only by the human backstop and the independent kill-cord. **[UNVERIFIED]**. |
   243	| **H7** | **Human-override failure** — the backstop human fails to respond, is incapacitated/displaced, or the override is unusable. | Human distracted/overboard/incapacitated; kill-cord unclipped; manual override mis-wired. | Escalation ladder (§3.2) to command attention; the deliberate design that software never auto-manoeuvres, so an unresponsive human does not cause a surprise manoeuvre; kill-cord fires if the helm is displaced; pre-trial checklist (kill-cord clipped, override tested); qualified-person-aboard is a baseline precondition. | If the human is incapacitated *at* the helm (kill-cord not pulled) with authority already revoked, the vessel continues at its last physical state until intervention/fuel exhaustion. Irreducible for a manned system whose sole safety actor is unresponsive; out of software scope by design; requires an operational control (e.g. second crew / helm dead-man). **[UNVERIFIED]/accepted**. |
   244	| **H8** | **Steering on a spoofed/absent frequency-reference or heel-biased solution** (supporting row, from the baseline degradation contract). | Frequency reference degrades or sustained heel steps the drift model beyond what the clock states absorb; both magnetometers lost. | Reject biased Doppler per integrity; revoke via G2 when solution limits exceeded; heading protection bound revokes when both magnetometers are gone; mount the g-sensitivity vector vertical (baseline hardware rule). | Slow, in-model bias below the innovation-detection floor. **[UNVERIFIED]**; bounded by conservative limits and the human backstop. |
   245	
   246	---
   247	
   248	## 5. Assumptions and the [UNVERIFIED] register
   249	
   250	Safety-relevant items this case depends on that are not yet frozen:
   251	
   252	- Per-epoch **protection-limit numbers** for horizontal position, horizontal velocity and
   253	  heading, in both the aided and denied profiles (distinct from the acceptance-profile trial
   254	  statistics). Must be no looser than the profiles imply.
   255	- **`t_lease`** (watchdog deadline), constrained `< GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (4000 ms); provisional
   256	  few-hundred-ms to ~1 s.
   257	- **`T_ack`** and the caution-band hysteresis thresholds/dwell for the escalation ladder.
   258	- ArduPilot **GPS/EKF failsafe parameter values** proving loss/degradation of `GPS_INPUT`
   259	  cannot auto-manoeuvre; validated in SITL against a pinned firmware commit + artifact
   260	  checksum.
   261	- Whether **MAVLink signing** is available on the pinned firmware for the companion link.
   262	- The mechanism of "stop steering" at the MAVLink boundary (mode command vs fix-validity
   263	  degrade) that reliably yields helm control **without** provoking an ArduPilot failsafe
   264	  manoeuvre.
   265	- All timing budgets assume a **displacement hull**; a planing/slamming hull invalidates them
   266	  (baseline caveat) and requires re-derivation.
   267	- Content-liveness (not just sequence-freshness) check to fully close hazard H4.
   268	
   269	Assumptions carried from the baseline: manned displacement-hull vessel, Danish straits
   270	(working assumption), qualified helm aboard with physical controller-independent override,
   271	`gnss_authority` enforced at bus ingress, and the MAVLink `GPS_INPUT` interface named by the
   272	baseline. Implementation-level field encodings and parameter names are subordinate v2
   273	schema/code and configuration work.

